14 months of exclusively breastfeeding. 

And I have to be honest with you, the past two months I thought I was going to call it quits. It’s been hard. Luna has wanted nothing but mama and the overstimulation has been rough. 

What’s getting me through and motivating me to keep going is watching the comfort it still brings her and reminding myself that one day she won’t need me as much. 

BUT! If I need to stop for my mental health and sanity, I certainly will. Because a happy mama is more important then hitting a certain amount of time or falling into the pressure of having to breastfeed at whatever cost. No. When I’m ready to stop, I will, and I will feel no guilt over it. No mom should. Whether you breastfed or pumped for a day, week, month, year or whatever, and you need to stop for your overall happiness, do it. Do it and feel proud. You have done amazing things and should be celebrated. Go mama!

——————————————————————-

I’ve felt the pressure to homeschool for many reasons. 

The first and main one is safety. The world today is so ugly and seeing so much tragedy has gotten the best of me. 

The second is because I’m a SAHM. I feel like most SAHMs also homeschool their kids. I wanted to. I truly did. But I know I wasn’t built for it. I knew I would not provide an environment that she would thrive in. I knew her personality, and staying home would cause more harm. Yes, I understand there are communities, but we’ve done such and she did not grow the same way she has going to school. So I put her in school. 

It was hard and I struggle with it daily. But I truly know I made the best decision for her and that was all that mattered. 

You’re an amazing mom if you homeschool. You’re an amazing mom if you send your kids to school. You made the best choice for you and your little ones and that’s all that matters. 
.
.
.

To the mom who’s sick and cant take a day off.

The mom that has to push through the body aches, headaches, flu, covid, mystery cold of the week, and keep running a home. Nursing your little ones. School and homework. Cleaning. Work. And who knows what else. 

To the mom who’s house just expects you to keep going and misjudges how sick you really are because you don’t complain, you just keep going. 

To the mom who cries because everything hurts, your bed calls your name, but you walk past it because so do your little ones.

I see you. 
I hear you.
I’m sorry you’re going through this right now. 
But you will feel better. 
You will get there. 
And just in case no one has told you, you’re an amazing mom and you’re doing a great job. 
.
.
.

And from the 5 things I’ve listed, my reason was number 1. I did it for my own mental health. I’ve become extremely irritable and stressed in my journey. As my daughter got older, she wanted to latch even more. The constant physical touch, having my shirt pulled, hair pulled, screaming unless I was around, became too much for me. I knew I have it in me to keep going, but I did need small breaks during the day. These breaks would give me the space I needed so when I did nurse, it was enjoyable for the both of us. 

It took me about 2 month to make this decision because of the guilt I felt. But once I reassessed myself, my value and worth, I knew I made the best decision for both of us and that’s what mattered. 

You are super woman. And on this journey you will have to make big decisions. Make sure you are making them for you. What makes you happy. And what keeps you at peace. You’re doing an amazing job. 
.
.
.

Christmas morning has to be my favorite morning of the year. 

Getting to see all our family, eat amazing food, and simply thanking God for all He has given us. 

Social media can easily make you feel that Christmas is about how many presents you were able to put under the tree. A sense of competition. Needing to post a picture with more presents then the person before you. 

Coming from a home where some years our tree looked a little bare, I learned that it’s not what’s under the tree, but who’s around it. I’m thankful that in those years of struggle, social media did not exist to make my family feel worse. 

This Christmas post pictures of what matters, family, love, and happiness. Celebrate your blessings in silence with your loved ones. Be thankful that you were blessed to gift your loved ones with a small token of appreciation. 

Remember not everyone can do what you did and feel heartbroken about it. So staying humble will bless more homes then you know. 

Have a beautiful and safe Christmas!
.
.
.

Hello 2023! Mama is ready for you! 

The last few months of 2022 I slowed down on my social media content. I go through moments of feeling lost and not finding my voice. Not knowing what message I want to convey or what I want to stand for. I got lost in motherhood and forgot about myself. Something I always say not to do. 

2023 we have so much! We are taking a trip to see if a new state will be our new home. Izabella starts Kindergarten. Focusing on Oh Mother on a different level. And focusing on me. Making sure mama is happy so my home is happy. Just to name a few. 

I’m excited to see what this year will hold for us. For me. I’m excited to see the woman, mother and wife I’ll transform into and what energy will build in our home. 

I vow to preserve my energy by welcoming new relationships that promote positivity and empowerment. And eliminating relationships that are draining, one sided, negative and unhealthy. I hope you do the same!

I’m ready. The mom in me, wife in me, woman in me is ready. Let’s get started. 
.
.

It took 2 months of mom guilt before deciding to cut back on the number of times I breastfed my daughter in a day. 

When my daughter turned one, breastfeeding changed. How she behaved towards me and breastfeeding became very overwhelming. People said it’s normal and to push through it, and I tried. 

I started to hate the journey. Annoyed when she would reach up for me. The screams were like nails on a chalk board. The pinching, scratching, pulling, biting, clogged milk ducts. I couldn’t take it anymore. I was short tempered, moody, and I knew something had to change fast. 

I wanted to quit all together but first I decided to introduce a bottle and cows milk. This way dad and grandma could help me. For more than half of the day I changed her feedings to bottle feedings. Still nursing her to sleep, at night, first thing in the morning and maybe 1-2 times during the day. This gave me about 6-8 hours a day of personal space i so desperately needed. Instantly my mood changed. I felt some freedom. Happiness. And could reflect on my journey feeling peace and not frustration. I didn’t want to stop breastfeeding. But I did want to slow down. And when I put the guilt aside and did what’s best for me, I became a very happy mama. 

Your journey needs to be more about you then baby. Without a happy and healthy moon, baby and your home will not thrive. Do what’s best for you
.
.
.

Because I’M READY!

And that’s all the reason I need. I received a lot of hate in those mom “support” groups when I discussed me situation. I received comments like:

- Your baby isn’t ready, why force her?
- If your body is producing, why force it to stop?
- You should keep pumping. 

A lot of people feel like you have to sacrifice your mental and emotional health at all cost in order to successfully breastfeed. I feel the complete opposite. I was willing to continue as lost as I mentally could. And once what was compromised, I stopped. These comments hindered me. Giving me mom guilt and pushing longer then I should have. But once I stopped caring what other people though and only focused on me, I made the best decision for mama. That made all the difference. 

I recommend you do the same. It is no one’s journey but your own and no one has an open door to share their opinion on YOUR life. You happiness is ALWAYS PRIORITY. 
.
.
.

Moms! Start prioritizing your happiness! 

Not enough time, too tired, don’t want to spend the money, are some of the things I kept saying that would prevent me from doing things that brought me joy. 

Small workouts, cooking, creating content all came to a stop because I needed to make sure everyone else was good. I felt miserable. I started to look in the mirror and hate what I see. I felt overweight, unmotivated, unhealthy, and just miserable. 

So I went back to me. Came up with a schedule that would give me time to invest in me. Stopped having excuses and just went for it. And in the short time, I started to feel like myself again. It feels so good. 

I told myself I wouldn’t loose myself in motherhood and wife life, but it’s hard. You get so caught up, busy, that you push your wants and needs aside so that everything else gets done. Until you have a melt down and wonder why in the world you feel so frustrated and empty. 

You’re going to loose yourself in life. It happens. Just don’t loose yourself for too long. Pull yourself back up and invest back into yourself. You’re worth it. 
.
.
.

My parents divorced when I was 3.

I was never been upset at my parents for making that decision. Because as hard as that was, I feel staying in an unhappy marriage would have been even harder and more damaging to the children. 

However, sometimes I wonder what it feels like. When my girls have both their mom and dad together, attending all their events together, eating breakfast, lunch and dinner together. What does that feel like? I secretly wish I was them at times. Just for a moment. To feel what they feel when they have those moments. The moments where mom and dad are in the kitchen laughing, play fighting, and hugging. I wish in my memory, I had those moments. 
.
.
.

My family needed me. 

My girls needed me. My marriage needed me. My home needed me. So I slowed down on everything else and focused on them. 

I stopped posting as consistent as before. I know one day I will get back to the game, but right now my home needed me. 

I want to say I’m those content creators that work through hardship but I don’t. Maybe that’s why I don’t have a million followers. But that’s never been my priority. 

My priority have always been my family before all else. Along with bringing you honest ,wholesome, mom life content. So here I am. Trying deeply to learn my kids and become the mom they both need me to be, prioritizing my own happiness, all while trying to find my husband in the middle of it all. 

Life isn’t hard in a bad way right now. It’s just challenging. Nothing I didn’t expect. But more overwhelming then what I did. So excuse me while I take a small break. To focus on me. To focus on my girls, to focus on my marriage, and building a new dynamic. I can feel deep down in my soul that something great is coming. I just need to be still until then. 
.
.
.

I’m guilty of missing special moments because I was too focused on cleaning. 

Too focused on making the linen closet was organized. Too focused cleaning out the refrigerator. Too focused on getting all 5 loads of laundry cleaned and put away in one day. 

Moments when I hear my kids laughing in the distance, having fun and creating memories and instead of being there, I was too focused on a task that held no memories and would have to be repeated the next day. 

Am I saying to let your home get unmanageably out of control? No. I’m just saying that once in a while you may want to take a small break from cleaning to smell the roses. I know you’ll be happy you did. 
.
.
.

My dad passed away when I was 17.

All his family lives in a different state so I don’t have many moments to feel like I have him close. Ironically, Izabella started to ask about my dad this week so we have spoken about him more recently then we ever have. On Friday I received a surprise text that my grandparents, my dads parents, came to town so of course we had to visit. 

This was the first time they would meet Luna and see Izabella since she was born. 

Izabella doesn’t understand much. She knows my dad is with God and we were going to visit his mom and dad, her great grandparents. She is not social with people she’s never met or remembers. She is shy and stays away. But today she was so loving and affectionate. She took to them right away and my heart felt such joy. 

Before leaving we took this photo. It may be in my head, but the sky looked extra open, the sun seemed extra bright and in my heart I truly felt like we were not alone ❤️
.
.
.

I love spending time with my kids. 

But sometimes I need time alone. I’m overstimulated, exhausted, short tempered, and I know I’ve been pushed passed my limits and I now need time alone to reset. 

Setting boundaries and expectations with your kids is a great thing. It lets them know when they can and can’t do things with you. Sometimes they are disappointed when they can’t but in turn it makes the moments when they can that more special. 

I love cuddling with my kids at night and sharing food, but sometimes I don’t, and that’s okay too. In the moments I don’t I make sure to explain to my kids why we can’t have those moments today but we will pick back up on them when we are ready. 

Never feel bad for needing space. We are more than just moms. We are human beings with needs, wants and emotions and what we feels matters. What we need matters. We matter. 
.
.
.

If there is something I will never do is beg someone to respect me, my boundaries, my children, or my space. 

When I became a mother I wanted to do all I could to provide an environment where they felt peace, acceptance, respected, and empowered. I wanted our home to be their safe space. A place they wanted to come to not just on hard days but any day. I wanted a home filled with laughter not screams. A home that looks like it’s being used. Not a museum where my kids can’t play, though, or sit anywhere. No, my home is not perfect but overall, I believe we are achieving this. 

It’s not easy. There will be people in your life that see your boundaries and will simply disregard them. I’m not saying to not try to communicate your needs in hope that they will learn them and respect. But in the event they don’t, sometimes it’s best to simply walk away. Maybe one day your paths will cross again and a better relationship will flourish. In the mean time water the relationships that already are and wish the best to the ones that are not. 
.
.
.

What was your breastfeeding goal Vs. what you actually achieved?

Mine was 1 year. Once I hit that goal I realized I could go longer. I had to adjust my journey to fit where I was in that moment in time, but I was able to keep going. Now I’m 17 months in and nursing is truly second nature. It happens without me even noticing sometimes. I’m not sure when this journey will end or how. I definitely didn’t see it lasting this long so I’m assuming it will end unexpectedly too. 

I knew when I needed to introduce a bottle for help. I knew when I needed to slow down for my own mental health. So I know when it’s time to stop, I will know. 
And I know it’s not time. 
.
.
.

Which one do you like more? 1, 2, or 3? 

I’ve never been 100% comfortable in a bathing suit. 

I’ll put them on and continue my day, but in the back of my mind I always worry about all my imperfections people must be looking at and judging. 

My thighs are never smooth and always bruised. For some reason I can’t go a day without walking into something. My skin is never flawless and the sun leaves no room to hide it. I don’t have a flat tummy when I sit. And overall I’m just uncomfortable even though I do a pretty good job at hiding it. 

I’m more comfortable in one pieces now. So I got these 3 bathing suites (yes I’m OBSESSED with plants) and need help picking which one to take on my first mini getaway with BOTH my girls. Which one do you like?

We had to cut our first family trip short. 

Little Luna got super sick. Shes been such a trooper getting through, but it’s been rough on her so we decided to go home a little early. 

The short time we had was a blast. It was pure joy watching Izabella. The traveler in her awoke. She was game to go anywhere and have an adventure. The 4 hour drive to Georgia went seamless for her. She did not have a fear in the world and it was the most beautiful thing to watch.

This decision did not come to us lightly. 

I never imagined I would be a homeschool mom. I always pictures my children attending school just like I did, going to PTA meetings, and chaperoning field trips. It wasn’t until I had to enroll my daughter into VPK that my heart began to feel heavy. 

School shootings and the lack of care each state showed to make real changes for it to not happen again. Book bands. Regulating and restricting vital learning materials. Teacher strikes. Short staffed. Overcrowded classrooms are all things that initiated my curiosity towards homeschooling. 

I enrolled my daughter in VPK and convinced myself that in only a few weeks dropping her off and driving away would not send me into panic. 10 months later and my heart didn’t change. So the research began. 

Months of research. Will my daughter be socially awkward? Am I depriving her of a REAL education? Am I taking away a vital experience she should be having? Can I do this?! I drown myself in books, documentaries, speaking to other homeschool moms, listened to podcasts, followed social media platforms, and little by little my husband and I fell in love with homeschooling, its beauty, the endless potential and the undeniable benefits. 

This choice in no way takes away from traditional schooling, or minimizes the importance and value of teachers. But for us and our home, what we envisioned for our children, and the freedom we want to have, the choice for homeschool was made clear. 

If there is one word of advice I can give to people considering this is to ignore the world and the negative opinions they may have. Most of the time they are repeating what they hear from likeminded people. Not facts from intensive research and experience. You know you children best and that’s all that matters. You own no one an explanation of why you are choosing this and it is not your job to convince people that you are making the right decision for your children. Let them think what they want and simply walk away. You are going to love it! 
.
.
.

I can’t put into words how surreal this chapter in my life feels. Since I can remember my heart called out to a different place. But as much as I’d try to move, it never worked out. The timing was never right.

Happy National Breastfeeding Week

I am about a month shy of hitting 2 years of breastfeeding. My time is coming to an end. My supply has dropped significantly. Luna still nurses for milk but mainly comfort. I don’t take pictures anymore of my journey. This is a picture Izabella took without me noticing and I’m so glad she did. 

A normal feeding. Luna with something in her hand, moving around and me trying my best to enjoy the moment. It has been a great 2 years. I’ve made it SOOOO much further than I had hoped. 

We made it through the end of a pandemic. Formula shortage. Sicknesses. Daddy catching covid. And now a move. I’m so proud of us. Not everyday was beautiful. Somedays I wanted to hang up the towel. And other days I couldn’t wait to get back to you. I’m ok. This chapter will soon end an I’m ok. This is the last time I will breastfeed and soon this will only be a memory. A beautiful memory and I couldn’t be more proud. 
.
.
.

Today I used my last stash of breastmilk I had. 

I didn’t expect it to hurt as much as it did. But when I pulled them out the freezer and the first bag I pulled out  was the first bag I pumped for Luna, all the feels came over me. 

When I started this journey I didn’t know how long it would last. I lasted 4 months with Izabella and my goal was to make it longer then that. 2 years later and here I am. I still nurse Luna, but the sessions are a lot shorter and not as often. I know soon that chapter will also end. 

Letting go is hard. I am ready, but gosh is it hard. You don’t know how to feel. Should I have kept going? Did I force it? Did I fail her? You never feel 100% content with your choice. 

It’s a wave of mixed emotions and while some of them are of fear and doubt, others are of pride and strength. I did it! I didn’t just hit my goal, I surpassed it. I pumped and nursed through covid, a formula shortage, Izabella starting school, and now relocating states. I let go of control and told myself to let my body and Luna lead this journey, and they did. 

I thank my body daily for everything it’s done. I never take it for granted. This journey in no way signified my worth. I am valued regardless of how long or short this journey was. Or even being on it at all. It simply was a testimony of what I was capable of doing when I put my mind to it and my body allowed it to happen. 

To my body, thank you for always reminding me of my strength and teaching me where my value is truly derived from. 
.
.
.

My dearest Luna,

For 2 years, 270 days I nursed you. 

I provided during a pandemic. Through a formula shortage. Through sicknesses. And challenging times. 

No, everyday was not beautiful. There were some really hard days. But then there WERE beautiful days. Days when feeding you brought us comfort. When you’d play with my hair and caress my face. When you’d hug me and fall asleep and reminded me of the beauty of this journey.

I didn’t track. You fed when you were hungry, I didn’t track how often, how long, how much, as long as you were healthy, I knew we were doing a great job. I gave myself grace. When I needed sleep daddy gave you a bottle. When you were still hungry after a feed, we gave you formula. Some days we covered when we fed in public, others days we didn’t. We did what was best for us.

I love you so much. And I hope you know that this decision to end this journey was not easy for me. I thought and prayed about it deeply and knew I knew it was time. 

From conceiving you, birthing you and raising you, you have been my greatest teacher. You have shown me my deepest strengths I never knew existed. And for that, I thank you so much. I love you, mommy.
.
.
.

Shining a light on homeschool. Because not every homeschool mom floats around in dresses, acting like a Princess, has their kids bake bread and has a picture perfect home. Or schedules every breath their kids will take for the day. 

Homeschooling is becoming a very normal thing. Even a trend. And with that comes the over the top pages. The pages that make it feel extreme. The pages that make it complicated. And make you feel you could never do it. They make you feel like you could never provide that environment so you don’t even try. (I feel that way with makeup). 

But I’m here to tell you that homeschool isn’t that complicated. It’s not all everything in the house is beige, by kid speaks 6 languages at the age of 3, I wake up at 2am to get dressed and beautiful for the day and wear fairytale dresses, I took my kids to Japan to see Cherry Trees not just read about them in a book. 

Sometimes it’s walking to your backyard and observing the trees. Or sitting in the front yard  and talk about seasons and watching how the animals around you prepare for the winter ahead. Sometimes you’re in sweat pants and a hat. With messy hair and no make up. Because that’s the reality of it. 

Homeschool is a beautiful and challenging experience that you ARE more than capable of achieving. Don’t let these over the top influencer pages convince you otherwise. 
.
.
.

#2023 allowed me to feel free. 

It allowed me to stop chasing people, friendships, family relationships and any other form of relationship that didn’t serve my overall better self. 

After almost 35 years in the same state, in a city I truly never felt like home in, my life finally lined up in a way that allowed me to move. I tried many, many times before, but it never worked out. Looking back at all those tries and failures, I realize God had a bigger plan. I truly feel I needed to become a wife a mom first. To build a life with my husband so we could make the best decision not only for our daughters, but family who chose to move with us. 

I am so grateful for this year. It was hard, but anything worth it never comes easy. Cheers to #2024. Can’t wait to see that great adventures it has coming our way. 
.
.

This has to be the most vulnerable post I’ve ever shared. 

My skin has to be the most sensitive topic I can ever talk about. My skin has been one of the main reasons I’ve cried myself to sleep, the thing that traumatized me the most in all of grade school and beyond, and why I use makeup as a crutch. 

I have tried EVERYTHING. Accutane, antibiotics, birth controls, cut out dairy, drank a gallon of water daily, exercised, used every over the counter and doctor prescribed creams, got blood work, purchased every machine possible…..nothing worked. I truly felt like I was a loss cause and I’d have to deal with this for the rest of my life. 

Last month during another flair up I decided to do some research one more time. Every dermatologist gave me the same routine and medicine as the last. There has to be more. The creams and pills are not working. Something inside of me is not right and I needed to find a dermatologist who would take their time with me. One who saw me as a person and not a number. 

Last month I found Amy Black, the owner of @radiancederm. She focuses on healing from within. Finding what is going on inside that is effecting the outside so much. We sat down for over an hour and had the most in depth consultation I’ve ever had with a dermatologist. My journey will be long. But for the first time in a long time I’m excited for my skin and motivated to work hard on it. I will be documenting my journey on my YouTube channel so if you haven’t already, make sure to subscribe to see my skin journey. My hope is to help other moms and women who are in my shoes. 
. 
.
.

3 things I do to include my 2 year old in homeschooling: 1. Have them watch a learning show while her sister does computer work. This gives her the feeling that her and her sister are doing the same thing. She is eager to be like her big sister and follows her lead. 

2. I provide multiple sensory activities while her sister does hands on activities. You want to find an activity for your younger “student”that is similar to their older siblings. This gets them involved and distracted while you dive more in debt with your older children and what they should be doing. 

3. I move the classroom outside. This is beneficial for all kids. Sometimes the fresh air does them good. Also nature is the perfect learning tool. We use twigs, rocks, leaves, and anything else we can find to help in the lesson. 

The key is to include them in as much as possible. This allows them to feel included and also build a love for learning. Doing this has excelled my 2 year old in learning. She has learned material that her 5 year old sister is in the process of learning, all because I provided small activities to do next to her sister and included her in as many activities as possible. 

Everyone wants to raise little Einstein and sometimes can feel a pressure to do 101 things for their toddlers. Often the pressure makes them forget….they are toddlers. Allow them to be toddlers, and as they progress they will clearly show you their strengths, weaknesses and passions. From there you can build a classroom that they love and look forward to going to. 
.
